@Barry Ancona 

Quite so!  And after all, Jonathan, it's a Saturday puzzle!  

Admittedly this one took me the longest time I can remember. (And I had to use Google for some fact-retrieval -- which I try to avoid doing as much as possible. In this case, I rationalize, getting unstuck outranks blank-stare frustration.)

@The X-Phile - I knew it (or, I'd seen it a few times in the past and remembered it was very unusual, for me at least) but I had no idea how it was spelled or how to pronounce it. 

There was a lot in this puzzle that I didn't know, until I had enough in the crosses to figure it out. For example I had never heard of Talon Airways, but when I had about half the letters from the crosses, I saw that it almost had to be APIA, SAMOA. Ditto for several other entries. 

This is why I LOVED this puzzle! Many learning opportunities -- and VERY good misdirects.

@CaptainQuahog - Ugh. Autocorrect got me. 

Talofa. Talofa. 

Although TALON AIRWAYS would be an awesome name for an airline -- or for a rock band!

@Amy 

Let me explain. No, there is too much. Let me sum up:
one who adds is one who sums.

@Bill
Responding to the thrown off portion of your post. As recently as Thursday I was thrown off by how easy I found most of the non-trick-related cluing and fill. Because it was Thursday,  I pretty much suspected almost anything I wanted to enter. (But I also feel in general that non-trick- related Thursday cluing has gotten easier.)
Today I was surprised about how many entries I was able to fill in on my first pass.  That's usually not a typical Saturday experience for me.  I do think this leaned more  to fact-based clues than other Saturdays.  I enjoyed it.

@Mark 

“One needs to have knowledge of the lowbrow, the highbrow, and everything in between to solve this one handily.”

I guess that explains why I enjoyed this so much. It made me feel like I have a diverse knowledge base.

@Rosemary 

This is Peter Gordon’s 130th NYT crossword. 

He also runs a website called Fireball Crosswords, which are supposed to be good but hard. (I’ve done the few that you can solve without subscribing.)

@Malcolm 
Last gasp? Uh, Mr. Gordon has had 130 puzzles in the NYT, and has been averaging 4-5 a year lately. Not to mention creating all the Fireball crosswords:
<a href="https://www.fireballcrosswords.com" target="_blank">https://www.fireballcrosswords.com</a>/

@Malcolm - Weird. 

Once I was on to the misdirect, FAMOUS POTATOES was an absolute gimme. And it gave me a chuckle. It isn't "tortured" by any reasonable definition of the word -- far from it. Why isn't it timely? 

You know, the constructors are not required to keep Malcolm's own peculiar knowledge base in mind when they build a puzzle. Believe it or not, there are other people out there who have different experiences and knowledge bases than YOU have, who have every right to enjoy a puzzle, too.

@Dave According to Google Books ngram viewer, written use of "USHES" has increased dramatically over the past ten years. I'm sure you can find examples if you look. Here's one of ushed:

2000, Jonathan Pearce, John-Browne's Body and Sole: A Semester of Life, BalonaBooks, published 2006, →ISBN, page 142:
And she is Mrs. Freundlich’s dear friend, so old Mark, who was acting as usher, ushed her and Mrs. Preene to seats right up in front next to Claire so Mrs. Shaw could scope out everything I did.

@Dave Definitely something I have said more than once at a wedding.

[breaking off smalltalk] "More family coming in, I guess I better go ush"

One can always find fun with the English language if one is so inclined. And after all, isn't that why word games exist?

@Eva H. Horrible comment. Terrible attitude!

No, but srsly... not everyone will like every puzzle, but from the comments it's clear that a lot of us liked this one. And certainly many didn't. I don't plan to count the votes, but a puzzle loved by many is probably not horrible. And some of these clues seem to be in the running for clue of the year, or at least of Lewis' next top five. [i.e. ID tags].  As is often suggested, examples of which clues you especially disliked might generate a useful conversation. 

So... take a deep breath and carry on. The Sunday puzzle just dropped here in NYC; perhaps it will be more to your liking. and there's always the archives! Ciao.

@Barry Ancona @ Vaer

I was just about to reply to Laura Stratton with something that combined your comments. 

I enjoy Natan Last's puzzles, but the proper names are often a challenge.

@Dan W

I too prefer the older puzzles but mainly because they’re more challenging. 

So I’ve been working my way through Saturdays and Sundays from the archive and have knocked off 93, 94 and 95, halfway through 96. Maybe that wouldn’t work for you if you already did them when first published but I was mainly a Globe and Mail crossword solver back then.
